[[File:Lemur catta - George Edwards.jpg|right|thumb|upright|alt=An old drawing of a ring-tailed lemur seated eating fruit, along with a profile view of the head and body.|The [[ring-tailed lemur]] was one of the first [[lemur]]s to be classified by Carl Linnaeus in 1758.]]
The '''[[Taxonomy|taxonomic history]] of [[lemur]]s''' dates back to 1758 when [[Carl Linnaeus]] first [[Biological classification|classified]] them, and the taxonomy remains controversial today, with approximately 70 to 100&nbsp;[[species]] and [[subspecies]] recognized, depending on [[Species problem|how the term "species" is defined]].  Having undergone [[Evolutionary history of lemurs|their own independent evolution]] on Madagascar, lemurs have diversified to fill many [[Ecological niche|niches]] normally filled by other types of mammals.  They include the smallest primates in the world, and once included some of the largest.  Since the arrival of humans approximately 2,000&nbsp;years ago, lemurs have become restricted to 10% of the island, or approximately {{convert|60000|km2|sqmi}}, and many face [[extinction]].  Concerns over [[Lemur#Conservation|lemur conservation]] have affected lemur taxonomy, since distinct species receive increased conservation attention compared to subspecies.

The relationship between the [[aye-aye]] and the rest of the lemurs has had the greatest impact on lemur taxonomy at the [[Family (biology)|family]] rank and above.  Genetic analysis of this relationship has also clarified lemur [[Phylogenetics|phylogeny]] and supports the hypothesis that lemurs [[Oceanic dispersal|rafted]] to Madagascar.  Despite general agreement on phylogeny, the taxonomy is still under debate. At the [[genus]] level, the taxonomy has been relatively stable since 1931, but a number of additional genera have been recognized since then.

Since the 1990s, there has been a steep increase in the number of [[List of lemur species|recognized lemur species and subspecies]] through the discovery of new species, the elevation of existing subspecies to full species status, and the recognition of new species among previously known populations that were not even distinct subspecies.  Currently living lemur species are divided into five families and 15&nbsp;genera.  If the extinct [[subfossil lemur]]s are included, three families, eight genera, and 17&nbsp;species would be added to the count.  The recent rise in species numbers is due to both improved genetic analysis and a push in conservation to encourage the protection of isolated and distinct lemur populations.  Not everyone in the scientific community supports these taxonomic changes, with some preferring instead an estimate of 50&nbsp;living species.

==Background==
[[Image:Microcebus murinus -Artis Zoo, Amsterdam, Netherlands-8a.jpg|thumb|right|alt=A tiny, mouse-like lemur clings to a nearly vertical branch while looking down with its large eyes.|The [[mouse lemur]]s are the smallest primates in the world and also one of the most speciose of lemur genera.]]
Since their arrival on Madagascar, a [[biogeography|biogeographically]] isolated island with a unique mammalian fauna, lemurs have diversified both in behavior and morphology.  Their diversity rivals that of the monkeys and apes found throughout the rest of the world, especially when the recently extinct [[subfossil lemur]]s are considered.{{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|pp=85<U+2013>86}} Ranging in size from the {{convert|30|g|oz|abbr=on}} [[Madame Berthe's mouse lemur]], probably the world's smallest primate,{{LoM3 Sfn|p=124}} to the extinct {{convert|160|<U+2013>|200|kg|lb|abbr=on}} ''[[Archaeoindris fontoynonti]]'', the largest known [[prosimian]],{{LoM3 Sfn|p=37}}{{Sfn|Godfrey|Jungers|Burney|2010|p=356}}{{Sfn|Vuillaume-Randriamanantena|1988|p=379}} lemurs evolved diverse forms of locomotion, varying levels of social complexity, and unique adaptations to the local climate.  They went on to fill many niches normally occupied by monkeys, [[squirrel]]s, [[woodpecker]]s, and large grazing [[ungulate]]s.{{Sfn|Preston-Mafham|1991|pp=141<U+2013>188}}{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|p=110}}  In addition to the incredible diversity between lemur families, there has also been great diversification among closely related lemurs.{{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|pp=85<U+2013>86}}

The arrival of humans on the island 1,500 to 2,000&nbsp;years ago has taken a significant toll, not only on the size of lemur populations, but also on their diversity.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|p=110}}  Due to [[habitat destruction]] and hunting, at least 17&nbsp;species and 8&nbsp;genera have gone extinct and many others have become threatened.{{LoM3 Sfn|pp=1, 27}}  Historically, lemurs ranged across the entire island inhabiting a wide variety of habitats, including [[Madagascar dry deciduous forests|dry deciduous forests]], [[Madagascar lowland forests|lowland forests]], [[Madagascar spiny thickets|spiny thickets]], [[Madagascar subhumid forests|subhumid forests]], [[Cloud forest|montane forest]], and [[mangrove]].  Today, their collective range is restricted to 10% of the island, or approximately {{convert|60000|km2|mi2|abbr=on}}.{{LoM2 Sfn|p=17}}  Most of the remaining forests and lemurs are found along the periphery of the island.  The center of the island, the [[Central Highlands (Madagascar)|Hauts-Plateaux]], was converted by early settlers to [[Paddy field|rice paddies]] and [[grassland]] through [[Slash and burn|slash-and-burn agriculture]], known locally as ''tavy''.  As [[erosion]] depleted the soil, the cyclical forest regrowth and burning ended as the forest gradually failed to return.{{Sfn|Preston-Mafham|1991|pp=18<U+2013>21}}  In 2008, 41% of all lemur taxa were threatened with extinction while 42% were classified on the [[IUCN Red List]] as "[[Data Deficient]]".{{LoM3 Sfn|p=1}}

==Overview of taxonomic and phylogenetic classification==
[[File:Linnaeus1758-title-page.jpg|left|upright=0.6|thumb|alt=A book cover with the text "Caroli Linnaei Equitis de Stella Polari, Archiatri Regii, Med. & Botan. Profess. Upsal.; Acad. Upsal. Holmens. Petropol. Imper. Lond. Monspel. Tolos. Soc. Systema Naturae per Regna Tria Naturae, Secundum Classes, Ordines, Genera, Species, Cum Characteribus, Differentiis. Synonymis, Locis. Tomus I. Editio Decima, Reformata. Cum Privilegio S:ae R:ae M:tis Sveciae. Holmiae, Impensis Direct. Laurentii Salvii, 1758."|Lemurs were first formally classified in the [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|10th edition of ''Systema Naturae'']].]]
In the first volume of the [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|10th edition of ''Systema Naturae'']] (1758), [[Carl Linnaeus]], the founder of modern [[binomial nomenclature]], created the genus ''Lemur'' to include three species: ''Lemur tardigradus'' (the [[red slender loris]], now known as ''Loris tardigradus''), ''Lemur catta'' (the [[ring-tailed lemur]]), and ''Lemur volans'' (the [[Philippine flying lemur|Philippine colugo]], now known as ''Cynocephalus volans'').{{Sfn|Linnaeus|1758|pp=29<U+2013>30}}  Although the term "lemur" was apparently at first intended for [[loris]]es, it was soon applied to the [[endemism|endemic]] Malagasy primates, which have been known as "lemurs" ever since.{{Sfn|Tattersall|1982|pp=43<U+2013>44}} The name derives from the [[Latin]] term ''[[lemures]]'', which refers to the "spirits of the dead" from [[Roman mythology]].{{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|pp=85<U+2013>86}}  Linnaeus was familiar with the nocturnal habits and ghost-like appearance of lemurs and lorises,{{Sfn|Flower|Lydekker|1891|p=682}} as well as their noiseless movements at night, [[Tapetum lucidum|reflective eyes]], and ghostly cries. He may also have known about Malagasy legends that lemurs are the souls of their ancestors.{{Sfn|Nield|2007|p=41}} Being familiar with the works of [[Virgil]] and [[Ovid]] and seeing an analogy that fit with his naming scheme, Linnaeus adapted the term "lemur" for these nocturnal primates.{{Sfn|Blunt|Stearn|2002|p=252}}

Since the first taxonomic [[biological classification|classification]] of lemurs, many changes have been made to lemur taxonomy.  Within the primate order, [[treeshrew]]s (order Scandentia) were considered basal, prosimian primates<U+2014>close relatives of lemurs<U+2014>until the 1980s.{{Sfn|Rowe|1996|p=13}} [[Colugo]]s, also incorrectly referred to as "flying lemurs", were once considered lemur-like primates, but were reclassified as close relatives of bats,{{Sfn|Rowe|1996|p=27}} and more recently as close relatives of primates within their own order, Dermoptera.{{Sfn|Jane<U+010D>ka|Miller|Pringle|Wiens|2007}}  Primates, together with their closest relatives, the treeshrews, colugos, and long-extinct [[Plesiadapiformes|plesiadapiform]]s, form the taxonomically unranked [[Euarchonta]] [[clade]] within the [[Euarchontoglires]]. [[Lorisidae|Lorisids]], some of which were originally placed in the genus ''Lemur'' by Carl Linnaeus, have since been moved into either their own infraorder (Lorisiformes) or their own superfamily (Lorisoidea) within Lemuriformes.{{MSW3 Sfn|Groves|id=12100002|heading=Strepsirrini}}{{Sfn|Godinot|2006|p=446}}

For the Malagasy primate fauna, taxonomic nomenclature proliferated during the 1800s, with the aid of museum [[systematics|systematists]], such as [[Albert G<U+00FC>nther]] and [[John Edward Gray]], as well as naturalists and explorers, such as [[Alfred Grandidier]].{{Sfn|Jolly|Sussman|2006|p=25}}{{LoM3 Sfn|pp=48<U+2013>49}}  This nomenclature was not sorted out until decades later, when [[Ernst Schwarz]] standardized it in 1931.{{LoM3 Sfn|p=49}}{{Sfn|Schwarz|1931}}  It was not until the 1990s that this nomenclature started to see a new wave of taxonomic change.{{Sfn|Tattersall|2007|p=14}}
