The classification of several lemur taxa has elicited particular debate. Most significantly, the placement of the aye-aye has been controversial since its introduction to Western science in 1782, and it has been a topic of debate until very recently.{{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|pp=85<U+2013>86}}{{Sfn|Tattersall|1982|pp=246<U+2013>247}}{{Sfn|Sterling|McCreless|2006|pp=159<U+2013>160}}  Arguing against [[Charles Darwin|Darwin]]'s theory of [[natural selection]], [[Richard Owen]] claimed in 1863 that the aye-aye's distinct characteristics, including its ever-growing [[incisor]]s and unique, highly flexible middle finger, are so perfectly adapted for their uses in extractive [[foraging]] that they could not have evolved gradually through natural selection.{{Sfn|Sterling|McCreless|2006|p=159}}  More recently, the aye-aye's placement has posed problems for the rafting hypothesis for the primate colonization of Madagascar.  If this species does not form a [[Monophyly|monophyletic group]] with the rest of the lemurs, then multiple colonization events would have had to occur to explain the occurrence of lemurs on Madagascar.{{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|pp=85<U+2013>86}}

[[File:Aye-Aye (Chiromys madagascariensis).png|thumb|left|alt=Aye-aye (a lemuriform primate with large head, ears, and eyes; black, wiry fur; long, bushy tail; and hands with one unusually thin and long middle finger) perched on a branch|The [[aye-aye]] has traditionally been difficult to classify due to its unique physical traits.]]
Until Owen published a definitive anatomical study in 1866, early naturalists were uncertain whether the aye-aye (genus ''Daubentonia'') was a [[primate]], [[rodent]], or [[marsupial]].{{Sfn|Sterling|McCreless|2006|pp=159<U+2013>160}}{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=257}}{{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|pp=205<U+2013>207}}{{Sfn|Owen|1866|p=36}}  In the late eighteenth century, for example, the aye-aye was classified under the squirrel genus ''[[Sciurus]]''.{{Sfn|Elliot|1907|p=552}}  By emphasizing its primate features, such as its [[postorbital bar]], [[Stereopsis|stereoscopic vision]], and [[thumb|opposable hallux]], over its rodent-like teeth, Owen demonstrated its affinity with other primates.{{Sfn|Sterling|McCreless|2006|pp=159<U+2013>160}}{{Sfn|Owen|1866|p=96}}  In 1996, Ankel-Simons demonstrated that the shape and arrangement of the aye-aye's diminutive [[deciduous tooth|deciduous incisors]] indicate that this genus has a shared ancestry with the [[toothcomb]]ed primates.{{Sfn|Simons|1997|p=144}}  However, the placement of the aye-aye within the primates remained problematic until very recently.  The [[karyotype]] of the aye-aye is noticeably different from that of its closest relatives, the lorises and the rest of the lemurs, with a [[Ploidy#Diploid|diploid]] [[chromosome]] count of 2n=30.{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|p=544}}  Based on its anatomy, researchers have found support for classifying the genus ''Daubentonia'' as a specialized [[Indriidae|indriid]], a [[Cladistics|sister group]] to all strepsirrhines, and an indeterminate taxon within the primates.{{Sfn|Yoder|2003|p=1242}} In 1931, Schwarz labeled the aye-aye as an offshoot of Indriidae, claiming that all lemurs were monophyletic,{{Sfn|Schwarz|1931|p=400}} whereas [[Reginald Innes Pocock]] had previously placed the aye-aye outside of the lemurs.{{Sfn|Pocock|1918|pp=51<U+2013>52}}  In that same year, Anthony and Coupin classified the aye-aye under infraorder Chiromyiformes, a sister group to the other strepsirrhines.  Colin Groves upheld this classification in 2005 because he was not entirely convinced the aye-aye formed a clade with the rest of the Malagasy lemurs,{{MSW3 Sfn|Groves|id=12100096|heading=Chiromyiformes}} despite molecular tests that had shown Daubentoniidae was basal to all Lemuriformes.{{Sfn|Yoder|2003|p=1243}}

{{cladogram|title=Competing lemur phylogenies
