Another interpretation of the aye-aye's origins has once again called into question the single origins of the lemurs.  The aye-aye and a fossil strepsirrhine primate from Africa, ''[[Plesiopithecus]]'', share similarities in the shape of the skull and the morphology of the lower jaw, which suggest that the latter could be a primitive relative of the aye-aye.  However, the placement of an aye-aye ancestor in Africa would require multiple colonizations of Madagascar by strepsirrhine primates.  Molecular tests may offer support, since they show that the aye-aye was the first to diverge in the lemur clade and that the other lemur families did not diverge until much later.{{Sfn|Godinot|2006|p=457<U+2013>458}}{{Sfn|Chatterjee|Ho|Barnes|Groves|2009|pp=3, 5}}

Often classified with the galagos by early students, the cheirogaleids (dwarf and mouse lemurs) were placed with the other lemurs from Gregory's 1915 classification until the early 1970s, when several anthropologists proposed that they were more closely related to lorisiforms, based on morphological data.{{Sfn|Tattersall|1982|pp=246<U+2013>247}}{{Sfn|Groves|2001|p=55}} However, relevant genetic studies unanimously place cheirogaleids within the lemuriform clade and Groves himself, who had promoted the cheirogaleid-lorisiform relationship in a 1974 paper, by 2001 regarded the idea as refuted.{{Sfn|Yoder|2003|pp=1242<U+2013>1243}}{{Sfn|Groves|2001|p=55}}

Classifications in the first half of the 20th century divided lemurs into three families: Daubentoniidae, Indriidae, and Lemuridae, with the latter including the current Cheirogaleidae and Lepilemuridae.{{Sfn|Tattersall|1982|pp=246<U+2013>247}} Because of concerns that Lemuridae might not be monophyletic, the family was later split; in 1982 Tattersall separated the Cheirogaleidae for the dwarf lemurs, mouse lemurs and relatives, and the Lepilemuridae for the sportive lemurs and bamboo lemurs (including the [[greater bamboo lemur]]).{{Sfn|Tattersall|1982|p=263}} This classification is still used, except that the bamboo lemurs were moved back to Lemuridae.{{Sfn|Mittermeier|Ganzhorn|Konstant|Glander|2008|p=1628}}{{MSW3 Sfn|Groves}}

From the 1970s to the 1990s, there have been suggestions that the ruffed lemurs might be related to indriids or a sister group to Lemuridae and Indriidae and that the bamboo lemurs are related to the sportive lemurs,{{Sfn|Groves|2001|pp=54<U+2013>55}} but neither view is supported by molecular phylogeny.{{Sfn|Horvath|Weisrock|Embry|Fiorentino|2008|loc=fig. 1}} The sportive lemurs and the extinct [[koala lemur]]s (Megaladapidae) both lack upper incisors in the permanent dentition,{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|p=248}}{{Sfn|Godfrey|Jungers|2002|p=112}} and in 1981, Groves placed both together in the family Megaladapidae, which he renamed Lepilemuridae in 2005 because that older name [[Principle of Priority|takes precedence]].{{MSW3 Sfn|Groves|id=12100065|heading=Lepilemuridae}} Genetic research does not support a close relationship between the sportive and koala lemurs and instead places the koala lemurs as a sister group to Lemuridae; therefore, the two are now placed in separate families (Lepilemuridae for the sportive lemurs and Megaladapidae for the koala lemurs).{{Sfn|Orlando|Calvignac|Schnebelen|Douady|2008}}{{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|p=115}}{{Sfn|Karanth|Delefosse|Rakotosamimanana|Parsons|2005|p=5094}} The [[sloth lemur]]s (Palaeopropithecidae) and [[monkey lemur]]s (Archaeolemuridae) were classified as subfamilies within Indriidae as late as 1982,{{Sfn|Tattersall|1982|p=263}} but are now recognized as separate families.{{Sfn|Orlando|Calvignac|Schnebelen|Douady|2008|p=2}}

The relationships among the families of lemurs have been problematic and have yet to be definitively resolved.  Two competing [[phylogenetics|phylogenies]] exist based on genetic and molecular data.  One approach (Horvath ''et&nbsp;al''.) looks at a larger number of genes, but among fewer species.  This results in Lemuridae being a sister group to Lepilemuridae, Cheirogaleidae, and Indriidae.{{Sfn|Horvath|Weisrock|Embry|Fiorentino|2008|loc=fig. 1}}  The other approach (Orlando ''et&nbsp;al''.) looks at fewer genes, but more lemur species.  Using this analysis, Lepilemuridae becomes the sister group to Lemuridae, Cheirogaleidae, and Indriidae.{{Sfn|Orlando|Calvignac|Schnebelen|Douady|2008|loc=fig. 1}} Both phylogenies agree that the Malagasy primates are monophyletic and that Daubentoniidae (the aye-aye) is basal to the lemuriform clade, having split off significantly earlier than the other families.{{Sfn|Yoder|2003|p=1243}}{{Sfn|Horvath|Weisrock|Embry|Fiorentino|2008|loc=fig. 1}}{{Sfn|Orlando|Calvignac|Schnebelen|Douady|2008|loc=fig. 1}}  However, two problems create complications for both approaches.  First, the four most closely related living lemur families diverged within a narrow window of approximately 10&nbsp;million years, making it much harder to distinguish the splits with molecular evidence.  In addition, these families diverged from their last common ancestor approximately 42&nbsp;mya; such distant splits create a lot of [[Statistical noise|noise]] for molecular techniques.{{Sfn|Yoder|Yang|2004|p=768}}

==Genus-level classification==
[[File:Babakotia radofilai.jpg|thumb|right|alt=A giant lemur hangs from a tree limb by all four feet like a slow-moving sloth. The tail is short, and the arms are slightly longer than the legs.|The naming of the extinct ''[[Babakotia|Babakotia radofilai]]'' in 1990 added another genus to the list of subfossil lemurs.]]
Early distribution of lemur species among genera differed in a number of ways from current taxonomy. For example, the [[fork-marked lemur]]s were initially placed in ''Lemur'' and then in ''Microcebus'' with the mouse lemurs before being placed in their own genus ''Phaner'',{{Sfn|Schwarz|1931|p=406}}{{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|p=111}}{{MSW3 Sfn|Groves|id=12100027|heading=''Phaner''}}{{Sfn|Groves|2001|pp=65<U+2013>66}} and [[Charles Immanuel Forsyth Major]] split the ''Cheirogaleus medius'' species group of the dwarf lemurs into a separate genus ''Opolemur'', but this was not accepted.{{Sfn|Schwarz|1931|p=404}}{{Sfn|Groves|2001|pp=65<U+2013>66}} Genus-level taxonomy was largely stabilized by Schwarz in 1931,{{Sfn|Schwarz|1931}} but a number of later changes have become accepted:

* The [[ring-tailed lemur]], [[ruffed lemur]]s,  and true lemurs were once grouped together in the genus ''Lemur'' due to a host of morphological similarities.  For instance, the skeletons of the ring-tailed lemur and the true lemurs are nearly indistinguishable.{{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|p=146}} However, ruffed lemurs were reassigned to the genus ''Varecia'' in 1962,{{MSW3 Sfn|Groves|id=12100059|heading=''Varecia''}} and due to similarities between the ring-tailed lemur and the bamboo lemurs, particularly in regards to molecular evidence and scent gland similarities, the brown lemurs were moved to the genus ''Eulemur'' in 1988.{{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|p=146}}{{LoM3 Sfn|p=315}}{{MSW3 Sfn|Groves| id = 12100034 | heading = ''Eulemur''}} The genus ''Lemur'' is now [[monotypic]], containing only the ring-tailed lemur.
* In 2001,  Colin Groves concluded that despite similarities, the greater bamboo lemur was sufficiently distinct from the [[bamboo lemur]]s of the genus ''Hapalemur'' to merit its own monotypic genus, ''Prolemur'',{{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|p=144}}{{MSW3 Sfn|Groves| id = 12100057 | heading = ''Prolemur''}}  in contrast to Schwarz's 1931 disagreement with Pocock's decision to separate ''Prolemur'' from ''Hapalemur''.{{Sfn|Schwarz|1931|p=407}}
* Originally placed in the genus ''Microcebus'' ([[mouse lemur]]s), the [[giant mouse lemur]] was moved to its own genus, ''Mirza'', in 1985 due to its larger size, morphological differences, dental characteristics, and behavior.{{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|p=108}}{{MSW3 Sfn|Groves| id = 12100025 | heading = ''Mirza''}}
* The [[hairy-eared dwarf lemur]] was first placed in the genus ''Cheirogaleus'' ([[dwarf lemur]]s)  in 1875 and was later found to have closer affinities with ''Microcebus''.  However, its dentition and cranium structure were held sufficiently distinct to merit elevation to its own genus, ''Allocebus''.{{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|p=108}}{{MSW3 Sfn|Groves| id = 12100006 | heading = ''Allocebus''}}
* In 1948, paleontologist [[Charles Lamberton]] proposed a new sub-genus for the giant ruffed lemurs, ''[[Pachylemur]]'', which had previously been placed in the genus ''Lemur''.  Since the 1960s, it has been considered its own separate genus, although the two extinct species of giant ruffed lemur have sometimes been grouped under ''Varecia'' with their closest relatives.{{Sfn|Godfrey|Jungers|2002|p=105}}
* A new genus of [[sloth lemur]], ''[[Babakotia]]'' was named in 1990.{{Sfn|Godfrey|Jungers|2002|p=102}}

==Species-level classification==
{{mainlist|List of lemur species}}
There is widespread disagreement on aspects of species-level lemur taxonomy, particularly concerning the recent increase in the number of recognized species.{{Sfn|Tattersall|2007|pp=21<U+2013>22}}{{Sfn|Yoder|2007|p=866}}{{Sfn|Groeneveld|Weisrock|Rasoloarison|Yoder|2009|pp=2<U+2013>3, 12}}  According to [[Russell Mittermeier]], the president of [[Conservation International]] (CI), taxonomist [[Colin Groves]], and others, there are currently 101&nbsp;recognized species or subspecies of extant lemur, divided into five families and 15&nbsp;genera.{{LoM3 Sfn|pp=100<U+2013>103}}  Conversely, other experts in the field label this as a possible example of [[taxonomic inflation]],{{Sfn|Tattersall|2007|pp=12, 21<U+2013>22}} and prefer instead an estimate of at least 50 species.{{Sfn|Yoder|2007|p=866}}  All sides generally agree that the recently extinct subfossil lemurs should be classified in three [[family (biology)|families]], eight [[genus|genera]], and 17&nbsp;species.{{Sfn|Gommery|Ramanivosoa|Tombomiadana-Raveloson|Randrianantenaina|2009}}{{LoM3 Sfn|p=34}}

[[Image:P verreauxi Grandidier.jpg|thumb|upright|left|alt=Drawing of a medium-sized lemur<U+2014>a sifaka<U+2014>with a dark crown clings vertically to a tree.|Many subspecies have been promoted to species status, yielding nine species for the genus ''Propithecus''.]]
Over the past two decades, the number of recognized lemur species has more than tripled according to some experts.  In 1994, 32&nbsp;distinct species were named in the first edition of [[Conservation International]]'s field guide, ''[[Lemurs of Madagascar (book)|Lemurs of Madagascar]]'',{{LoM1 Sfn|p=51}} and 68&nbsp;were described in the 2nd edition, published in 2006.{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=54<U+2013>55}}  In December 2008, Russell Mittermeier, Colin Groves, and other experts co-wrote an article in the ''International Journal of Primatology'' classifying 99&nbsp;species and subspecies.{{Sfn|Mittermeier|Ganzhorn|Konstant|Glander|2008|p=1608}}  In late 2010, the 3rd edition of ''Lemurs of Madagascar'' listed 101&nbsp;taxa.{{LoM3 Sfn|p=68}}  The number of lemur species is likely to continue growing in the coming years, as [[Field study|field studies]], [[Cytogenetics|cytogenetic]] and [[Molecular genetics|molecular genetic]] research continues, particularly on [[cryptic species]], such as mouse lemurs, which cannot be distinguished visually.{{Sfn|Yoder|2007|pp=866<U+2013>867}}

This threefold increase in less than two decades has not had universal support among taxonomists and lemur researchers.  In many cases, classifications ultimately depends upon which [[Species#Definitions of species|species concept]] is used. Due to the critical condition that most Malagasy primate populations are in, [[Taxonomy|taxonomists]] and [[conservation movement|conservationists]] sometimes favor splitting them into separate species to develop an effective strategy for the conservation of the full range of lemur diversity.{{Sfn|Yoder|2007|p=866}}{{Sfn|Mittermeier|Ganzhorn|Konstant|Glander|2008|pp=1609<U+2013>1614}} Implicitly, this means that full species status will help grant genetically distinct populations added environmental protection.{{Sfn|Yoder|2007|p=866}}

The first large wave of new lemur species descriptions came in 2000, when Colin Groves split two species of [[dwarf lemur]] (''Cheirogaleus'') into seven species{{Sfn|Groves|2000|p=943}} while [[Rodin Rasoloarison]] and colleagues recognized seven species of mouse lemur in western Madagascar.{{Sfn|Rasoloarison|Goodman|Ganzhorn|2000|p=963}}  Then in 2001, Colin Groves elevated the [[red ruffed lemur]] (''Varecia rubra''),{{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|p=170}}{{MSW3 Sfn|Groves| id = 12100060 | heading = ''Varecia rubra''}} five subspecies of brown lemur (''Eulemur albifrons'', ''E.&nbsp;albocollaris'', ''E.&nbsp;collaris'', ''E.&nbsp;rufus'' and ''E.&nbsp;sanfordi''),{{MSW3 Sfn|Groves| id = 12100040 | heading = ''Eulemur fulvus''}} and four subspecies of [[sifaka]] (''Propithecus coquereli'', ''P.&nbsp;deckenii'', ''P.&nbsp;edwardsi'', and ''P.&nbsp;perrieri'') to full species status.{{MSW3 Sfn|Groves| id = 12100084 | heading = ''Propithecus''}}  Additional elevations of all remaining subspecies within the ''Eulemur'' and ''Propithecus'' genera were made in the years that followed.{{LoM3 Sfn|p=377}}{{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|pp=149, 182}}  These and subsequent changes in taxonomy were largely due to a shift to the [[phylogenetic species concept]],{{Sfn|Thalmann|2006}} and are not universally endorsed.{{Sfn|Tattersall|2007|pp=19<U+2013>20}}

By far the most explosive growth in species numbers (in absolute terms) has been in the genera ''Microcebus'' and ''Lepilemur''. In 2006, 15&nbsp;new species of ''Lepilemur'' were described, with three new species reported in February,{{Sfn|Andriaholinirina|Fausser|Roos|Zinner|2006}} one in June,{{Sfn|Rabarivola|Zaramody|Fausser|Andriaholinirina|2006}} and 11 in September.{{Sfn|Louis|Engberg|Lei|Geng|2006}}  Since then, three additional species have been described, one of which turned out to be identical to a previously described species.{{Sfn|Mittermeier|Ganzhorn|Konstant|Glander|2008|pp=1624, 1628}} Genetic and morphological differences seem to suggest that they are cryptic species, but there is still debate whether these merit full species status or should be regarded as subspecies of previously identified, "core" species.{{Sfn|Tattersall|2007|p=18}}{{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|p=115}}

[[Image:Lepilemur sahamalazensis c.png|thumb|right|alt=A sportive lemur (small body, long legs, brown fur, large eyes, and thick, furry tail) clings to the side of a tree, with its head turned towards the camera.|The [[Sahamalaza sportive lemur]] (''Lepilemur sahamalazensis'') was one of many new sportive lemur species identified in the 2000s.]]
Both true lemurs and mouse lemurs were initially divided into a small number of species, either with no distinguishable [[subspecies]] (in the case of mouse lemurs){{Sfn|Yoder|Yang|2004|p=769<U+2013>770}} or with several distinguishable subspecies (in the case of true lemurs).{{Sfn|Johnson|2006|pp=188<U+2013>189}}  With molecular research suggesting a more distant split in both genera, these subspecies or undistinguished populations have been promoted to species status.{{Sfn|Yoder|Yang|2004|p=769<U+2013>770}}{{Sfn|Johnson|2006|pp=193<U+2013>194}}

In the case of mouse lemurs, the rise in species numbers has been only slightly less sudden and dramatic. Classified as one species by [[Ernst Schwarz]] in 1931 (excluding one, [[Coquerel's giant mouse lemur]], that is no longer classified in ''Microcebus''),{{Sfn|Schwarz|1931|pp=401<U+2013>403}} the genus was revised to contain two species, the [[gray mouse lemur]] (''Microcebus murinus'') and the [[brown mouse lemur]] (''M.&nbsp;rufus''), after an extensive field study in 1972 showed both living in [[sympatry]] in southeastern Madagascar.{{Sfn|Kappeler|Rasoloarison|2003|p=1310}}  At the time, the gray mouse lemur was known in the drier parts of the north, west, and south, while the brown mouse lemur inhabited the humid rainforest regions of the east.  However, we now know the [[species diversity]] and distribution to be significantly more complex.{{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|p=86}}  Revisions throughout the 1990s and 2000s identified numerous new species through genetic testing using [[mitochondrial DNA]], demonstrating that the genus is represented by a multitude of cryptic species.{{Sfn|Mittermeier|Ganzhorn|Konstant|Glander|2008|p=1615}}{{Sfn|Braune|Schmidt|Zimmermann|2008}}{{Sfn|Olivieri|Zimmermann|Randrianambinina|Rasoloharijaona|2007|p=309}}{{Sfn|Louis|Engberg|McGuire|McCormick|2008}}  Many, but not all of these defined species have been supported by [[nuclear DNA]] tests.{{Sfn|Weisrock|Rasoloarison|Fiorentino|Ralison|2010|pp=8<U+2013>9}}

However, there are still concerns that species are being identified prematurely.  [[Ian Tattersall]], an anthropologist who recognized 42 species of lemur in 1982,{{Sfn|Tattersall|1982|pp=40<U+2013>43}} has expressed concern that the geographically organized variety in lemur populations is being recognized with full species status while the number of subspecies in lemur genera has virtually disappeared.  He has argued that taxonomists are confusing differentiation and [[speciation]], two processes that are often unrelated, while denying the role of [[microevolution]] in evolutionary processes.{{Sfn|Tattersall|2007|pp=21<U+2013>22}}  Still other researchers who emphasize the framework of the "general lineage concept of species" contend that lineage divergence or differentiation demarcates the beginning of a new species.{{Sfn|Weisrock|Rasoloarison|Fiorentino|Ralison|2010|p=8}}

New species have been identified due to differences in [[Comparative anatomy|morphology]], karyotypes, cytochrome ''b'' sequences, and other genetic tests, as well as several combinations of these.{{Sfn|Tattersall|2007}}  When nuclear DNA (nDNA) was tested in conjunction with mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA) in mouse lemurs, a few species, such as [[Claire's mouse lemur]] (''Microcebus mamiratra'') were demonstrated to be indistinguishable from other closely related species.  In such cases, nDNA did not vary, but the mtDNA that had been used to define it as a species was still distinct.  Differences in results between nDNA, which is inherited from both parents, and mtDNA, which is inherited from the mother, was attributed to female [[philopatry]], where females remain within or close to the [[home range]] into which they were born while males disperse.  Since the isolated population known as Claire's mouse lemur has distinct mtDNA, but not nDNA, it is likely to contain a population descended from a related group of females, but which still disperses and interbreeds with nearby populations.{{Sfn|Weisrock|Rasoloarison|Fiorentino|Ralison|2010|p=11}}

Traditionally, karyology has been considered when determining species status.{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=544}}  For example, in 2006, three new species of sportive lemur were named based partly on karyotypes.{{Sfn|Andriaholinirina|Fausser|Roos|Zinner|2006}}  From the lemurs studied so far, the diploid number of chromosomes varies between 2n=20 and 2n=66.  In the case of the true lemurs, the diploid number ranges from 2n=44 to 2n=60 while the individual chromosome sizes vary considerably, despite strong similarities in morphology.{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=541<U+2013>544}}

Sometimes distinctions are made due to very slight differences in [[pelage]] coloration.  For instance, three distinctly colored types of mouse lemur were discovered in a multi-year study in [[Beza Mahafaly Reserve]] in southern Madagascar, but rather than being separate species, DNA tests revealed that they all belonged to a single species, the [[reddish-gray mouse lemur]] (''Microcebus griseorufus'').{{Sfn|Heckman|Rasoazanabary|Machlin|Godfrey|2006|p=1}} For this reason, further research is needed to confirm or deny the recent species splits.  Only through detailed studies of morphology, ecology, behavior, and genetics can the true number of lemur species be determined.{{Sfn|Yoder|2007|p=867}}

